            "answer_text": "Of course we can create gravitational waves. As a matter of fact\u2026 raise your arm. Shake your fist. There\u2026 you just created gravitational waves. Now that wasn\u2019t hard, was it? The trouble is, these will be exceptionally weak gravitational waves, on account of the fact that the coupling between matter and gravity is exceptionally weak. This is why you need something as humongous as the Earth (6 trillion trillion kilograms) to pull you down, and yet intermolecular forces (which are electromagnetic in nature) in a thin rope or cable are enough to counteract this force and keep you from falling. Another measure of how weak it is\u2026 as the Earth travels around the Sun, it, too, produces gravitational waves. Amounting to a few hundred watts. That is all. The entire Earth, all six trillion trillion kilograms of it, changes direction and reverses course every six months, amounting to a net velocity change of over 200,000 kph, yet it produces no more in the form of gravitational waves than the waste heat from a desktop computer. As you can imagine, what your fist produces is absolutely minuscule compared to that. And this is why we needed an exceptionally powerful event for a confirmed detection: The merger of two large black holes, releasing gravitational waves at such a stupendous rate that their energy output briefly exceeded the light output of the entire visible universe. So if your question is, can we produce gravitational waves with enough power to be detected by a realistic instrument? The answer, then, is no, not now, nor in the foreseeable future. ",
